{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:22:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:22:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18444"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74823"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7733"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25927"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is studying the number of mitotic figures observed in high-power microscope fields when examining breast cancer tissue samples. Each mitotic figure represents a cell undergoing division, and their occurrence is independent of other dividing cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes why the Poisson distribution would be appropriate for analysing this data?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The sample size needs to be greater than 30","The events are discrete and independent with a constant rate","The events must occur at regular intervals","The data follows a normal distribution","The variance must equal the sample size"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mitotic figures in this scenario represent discrete events occurring randomly within a fixed space (the microscope field). The \u003Cstrong\u003Eevents are discrete and independent with a constant rate\u003C/strong\u003E, making the Poisson distribution the appropriate choice for analysis. Each mitotic figure can be counted as a distinct event, and the occurrence of one dividing cell does not influence the likelihood of finding another.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe sample size needs to be greater than 30\u003C/strong\u003E - The Poisson distribution can be applied regardless of sample size\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe events must occur at regular intervals\u003C/strong\u003E - The Poisson distribution actually models random occurrences, not regularly spaced events\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe data follows a normal distribution\u003C/strong\u003E - The Poisson is a discrete probability distribution distinct from the continuous normal distribution\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe variance must equal the sample size\u003C/strong\u003E - In a Poisson distribution, the variance equals the mean, not the sample size\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Poisson distribution is particularly useful in medical research for analysing rare events that occur randomly but with a predictable average rate, such as disease occurrences, cellular phenomena, or radiation events.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Poisson distribution models rare events occurring in fixed time or space intervals.","The Poisson distribution is used when counting discrete events with independent occurrences."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T13:31:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T13:32:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74823"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i